3. History. The history of Carthage oceupies three periods :—

i. From the foundation to 13.C. 410, which is the period of the great development of her power.

ii. From ss.c. 410 to the commencement of her wars with Rome, ss.c. 264.

iii. The period of her decline and fall,13.c. 264 to ss.c. 146.

Of the first two os these periods it is beyond the purpose of this sketch to speak fully. It is enough to say that, partly from her superior situation, and partly, perhaps, from her being the latest and the favourite offspring of the mother state, partly from the shocks which the old Tyre received from the Assyrian and Babylonian conquestS‚ her importance became greatly and soon developed, until her supremacy was established, not only over the surrounding peoples, but over the older Phoenician colonies in Africa, —Tunis‚ Hippo, Hadrumetum, and even Utica.
